t effective innovation strategies hinge on attention to the context in which they are pursued. Instead of relying on a stale set of "best practices," executives must craft their own strategies based on the particulars of their industries and markets. But, there are some rules of the road that foster a triple bottom line; this book provides a research-based framework that outlines the critical capabilities necessary to drive sustainable innovation: a long-term commitment, nexus work, science and policy expertise, recombinant innovation, and robust design. Sustainable Innovation draws on a wide range of historical and contemporary examples to show business readers and their companies how to stand on the shoulders of successful pioneers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aIndustrial managementxEnvironmental aspects. 0aSocial responsibility of business. 0aSustainability. 0aTechnological innovationsxEnvironmental aspects. 4acapabilities. 4ainnovation strategy. 4ainnovation. 4astrategic planning. 4asustainability. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Green Business.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479502940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804795029423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804795029.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles